{"type":"message","id":"4e6fe984","parentId":"ba929cc6","timestamp":"2026-03-23T15:43:30.316Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_s1xzmvy1tbc2_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Session: 2026-03-23 15:43:08 UTC\n\n- **Session Key**: agent:main:main\n- **Session ID**: 5aee06a8-c808-422d-b59a-83abb6d1e792\n- **Source**: webchat\n\n## Conversation Summary\n\nassistant: The activations are all equalizing to ~0.22 — the decay rate is too high relative to diffusion, everything flattens. Let me fix the drift dynamics:\n\nassistant: Also fix `spark_drift` to seed properly:\n\nassistant: Still equalizing — the re-boost strategy isn't right for 133-node dense graphs. Let me check what `demo.py`'s `run_drift` actually does and use a proven approach:\n\nassistant: Now update `run_drift` to use goal-concepts seeding and the proven re-boost strategy:\n\nassistant: Update `spark_drift` to use the 4-value return:\n\nassistant: The literary cluster is too big (30 concepts all seeded at 0.95). Let me fix the seeding to pick just a subset:\n\nassistant: Let me step back and test with the `all` domain where the goal clusters are more distributed:\n\nassistant: The `all` domain works great. The literary cluster is too internally dense (32 literary devices all connected to each other, equalize every time). That's a graph topology issue. The fix is to just not add within-cluster edges for the literary cluster:\n\nassistant: Literary works now. Let me test the full pipeline including LLM generation via Ollama:\n\nassistant: \nFull pipeline works. Now test the FastAPI app itself:\n\nassistant: API imports clean. Let me commit all of this:\n\nassistant: The spark repo got polluted with workspace files. Let me clean it up properly:\n\nassistant: Clean slate. Now re-apply the API changes cleanly:\n\nassistant: Good — `engine.py` was reset. I need to re-apply. Let me write all three files fresh since I have them in memory:\n\nuser: Sender (untrusted